reviewText: m​ajor problems  in the grade section. some quizzes, tests or exams did NOT have a clear answer!! moreover a true/false question turned out wrong in both attempts - one time the answer true one time the answer false .  please test and consider reconfiguration.

A largely incoherent mess.  This course belabours many easy to grasp concepts in a scattergun approach but then airdrops references to irrelevant and complex notions.  Its nether well thought out nor well targeted to any particular audience.

Terrible course, it has absolutely nothing to do with the scope of the specialization (finance and strategy). The course goes entirely in boring, unintelligible and useless technicalities and computer concepts together with explaining the operation of programs and algorithms being suitable for a specialization in computer subjects but not for a program with a focus on finance and strategy. Duke must solve this type of errors since it puts its prestige at stake, it should eliminate this course from the specialization, or change the focus, lessons, tests and content towards a more practical and useful profile (show examples of practical uses of the technology and the potential business it can generate).
Good syllabus. The lecturer communicates clearly in terms of phonetics. He should improve on his explanation of contents including the key concepts.
I am having acute difficulty in the Week 2 Qiz #1 (Questions 3/5 &7...tried 5 times , need help !

This was supposed to be an intermediate course that focused on blockchain business models, but instead, focused mainly on such general blockchain information that was very unspecific to the subject it was supposed to be about. As someone already very knowledgeable about BTC, ETH, and how blockchain tech works, less than 20% of this course was new, useful information. I wanted to do a deep dive on the industry use cases but that was only a fraction of this course and did not go into real depth. Quite disappointed. The Duke courses on decentralized finance were way better.
Somewhat too US-centric towards the end. But otherwise great stuff!

Instructor spoke too slowly.  I solved that by using 1.5 speed.  Also, the working of the tests were poor.  I had to retake three of eight tests multiple times to pass, simply because the test question descriptions didn't match the instructor description of the materials at times.  I retook three tests at least three times each. That's not me failing tests, that's these tests were not well done.

The course was very well taught. However, the course content can be improved further by including more about implentation examples and challenges in businesses such as supply chain management. Also, the focus on regulatory laws can be reduced because they are highly country specific.

The content seems a little outdated because there has been a lot of progress made in the blockchain and cryptocurrency arena which is not covered in this course. Other than that the instructor and the course is wonderful.

This is a great course. The material is clear and in-depth. Cam Harvey is an excellent tutor. The weak point is the quizzes. For some questions, the wording is unclear. For many answers you have to guess what the person who came up with the questions was thinking. Although, that should not demotivate anyone from taking this course because, as I said before, the material is quite excellent.

The course provides a great insight into the Blockchain technology and different popular blockchain technologies available in the market. It also provides an overview on how the world will evolve with the increased use of Blockchain and scope for different business models etc. It is good course to venture into blockcha

Good content, but many of the quizzes have poorly worded questions. In particular, some of the TRUE/FALSE questions could be interpreted (reasonably) such that either answer is correct in certain states of the world. From the students perspective, this makes the grading seem arbitrary and pointless. This said, the video and slides are very informative.

E.g. in supply chain management. Maybe there was less to report at the time of recording, which I understand was 2019.Looking forward to any updates of this course!
